Metabolomics is an essential member of the modern 'omics sciences and has yielded numerous insights into connections between disease, health status and the small molecule content of cells.  The majority of metabolomics studies published to date are based upon LC-MS data, and fortunately, an increasing proportion of these studies provide access to tabulated or raw data that were generated.  Tabulated metabolomics data is typically formatted as compound-by-compound table of abundance values (typically, peak area or peak height) for all of the samples analyzed in the study.  It should also contain information regarding compound identity, often a compound name (when known) and a mass-to-charge (or neutral mass) and a retention time, metadata regarding sample or subject groups and related information, and ideally filename(s) for the associated raw data. Raw LC-MS data files will be in vendor-specific or generic (.mzml) format and should be linked to the tabulated data by filename.

We have developed a workflow to facilitate meta-analysis of multiple metabolomics datasets (in our case, datasets focused on physical activity). Our approach involves re-analysis of data from the tabulated level described above; when necessary, raw data files can be re-processed if tabulated data if not provided. We have established a workflow for formatting, upload, and meta-analysis of multiple independent metabolomics datasets which study a common biological effect -- in our case, the effect of an acute bout of physical activity on the metabolome of human plasma. The workflow differs slightly depending on whether the metabolomics data is targeted (named compounds only), untargeted (features annotated by mass and retention time only) or a hybrid of the two.  Within this repository are separate folders for targeted and untargeted metabolomics data workflows.  Data pre-processing steps and formatting requirements are detailed in the PREPROCESSING_targeted.txt and PREPROCESSING_untargeted.txt files within the folders. The folders also contain R scripts which contain code that can be used for meta-analysis of appropriately formatted metabolomics datasets from different studies, supporting correction for cofactors and allowing flexible assignment of sample groups to compare across studies. 

Please submit questions regarding these scripts to the repository host. We welcome feedback and questions.